{"cursor":"16482","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"s to provide near-total reflection of light over a limited range of\nwavelengths.]]\n\n'Thin-film interference' is the phenomenon that occurs when incident light\nwaves reflected by the upper and lower boundaries of a thin film interfere with\none another to form a new wave. Studying this new wave can reveal information\nabout the surfaces from which its components reflected, including the thickness\nof the film or the effective refractive index of the film medium. Thin films\nhave many commercial applications including anti-reflection coatings, mirrors,\nand optical filters.\n","linknr":239,"url":"Thin-film_interference","recorded":1362567187,"links":25,"instances":["optics","butterfly","wave_propagation","scientist"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Thin-film optics"],"headings":["Theory","Examples","Applications","History","See also","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/b/b3/Dielectric_laser_mirror_from_a_dye_laser.JPG/220px-Dielectric_laser_mirror_from_a_dye_laser.JPG","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/f/f1/Thin_film_interference.gif/300px-Thin_film_interference.gif","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/06/Dieselrainbow.jpg/300px-Dieselrainbow.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/5/2/2/522359592d78569a9eac16498aa7a087.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/4/c/6/4c6178dfaa098a34c2003619e7d7f0b6.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/d/f/c/dfc8573c574a63ee63594f9533183340.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/4/3/8436b648b8001f4b37ef8ee0eb611a76.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/e/a/6/ea691cf8b15bc23672e3e39fd89341cd.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/0/6/f/06f076978d34383c076aa2ced938b95b.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/a/4/7/a47a5fd30a245c